<DOC><DOCNO> AP880503-0234 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0128EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stadd   05-03 0500</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st add,0522</SECOND><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A surge in imports caused Japan's merchandise tradesurplus to fall 7.2 percent to $94.3 billion in the 1987 fiscalyear, the Finance Ministry has announced.   Monday's report confirmed the continuing strength of Japan'seconomy in spite of the strong Japanese yen, which hurts thecompetitiveness of Japanese products in domestic and overseasmarkets.   Exports grew 10.5 percet to $233.4 billion, but imports greweven faster, rising 26.9 percent to $139.1 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Italy's second-largest bank says it is seekingto acquire a majority stake in Irving Bank Corp., but analysts saythat swaying shareholders away from Bank of New York Co.'scompeting hostile bid remains an uphill battle.   Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, which had sought a 45 percentstake in Irving, said Monday it would seek to purchase 9.5 millionIrving shares, or about 51 percent of the New York-based bank, for$75 a share.   Bank of New York is offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of itsstock for each of Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding.</TEXT><DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United Auto Workers and ChryslerCorp. moved closer to a national contract settlement after wrappingup all but final details of related agreements covering formerAmerican Motors Corp. workers in Wisconsin, UAW Vice President MarcStepp said.   ``It means now we can turn our full attention to the nationaltalks. They're going very well,'' Stepp said Monday, adding thatsince last week, Chrysler management's ``attitude has changed forthe positive.''</TEXT><DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   As part of its inflation-fighting program,Mexico will hold the peso at its current value against the U.S.dollar until the end of the year, says Treasury Secretary GustavoPetricioli said.   Petricioli told local reporters that economic conditions permitthe government to continue a freeze on the exchange rate that hasbeen in effect since March. His remarks were reported in Monday'snewspapers.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Postal executives will be introduced this weekto a new breed of postal clerk that may never smile, but which alsonever frowns or gets cranky or takes a break when there's a linewaiting.   It's the new face of postal technology _ automated postal clerks_ and they will begin ``greeting'' the American public later thissummer.   One of the clerks, Infopost, answers customer questions. Theother, Autopost, weighs mail, takes money, makes change and sellspostage.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   On Wall Street Monday, blue-chip issues staged a modest rallybut the rest of the stock market lagged in a sluggish session. TheDow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.94 to 2,043.27.   The dollar was mixed against major currencies. Bond prices fell.   Precious metals futures prices plunged along with those forcrude oil and refined oil products following the failure of OPECoil ministers to agree on production cuts. Grain and soybeanfutures were mixed; cattle and livestock were mostly higher andstock-index futures advanced.</TEXT></DOC>